\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 DNSGroup Creation:\

\b0 \
To create a DNSGroup, an effort should be made (via a broadcast-request) to ensure the group doesn't exist already. This broadcast-request should be able to inform the node of all reachable groups, i.e. if I want to create "ccrg" I should first be aware of any existing "ccrg" groups AS WELL AS "soe.ucsc.edu", "inrg.soe.ucsc.edu", etc. By every group responding with its full name, I can quickly achieve a broad sense of the hierarchies available for me to join. In this example, rather than creating an autonomous, unreachable "ccrg.end" group it might be more advantageous to me to tell inrg.soe to advertise itself as reachable also for ccrg.soe and forward all the relevant requests to me :-).\
\
QUESTION: HOW DOES THIS AFFECT SCORING?\
\
After understanding the nearby "DNS topology" a node has three options: to join an existing group (and not create), to create an autonomous group, or to create a hierarchical group.\
\

\b Hierarchical Groups:\

\b0 These groups are where (presumably) the majority of discovery/resolution occurs. For a hierarchical group to be created, it must first coordinate and request permission from the group above it, which will be its "parent." This request/response mechanism serves to alert the parent group to its presence, verify there are no name-conflicts, and provides an opportunity to establish any necessary authentication/authorization (depending on the configuration of the network).\
\
