\b \cf0 Autonomous Groups:\

\b0 These groups are created ad-hoc and exist outside of any hierarchy (though I suppose they could also act as roots in starting their own hierarchy). The intent of autonomous groups is NOT to provide any sort of discovery or resolution outside of the group itself (either for convenience, network-policy, or security). These groups can be created by anyone, provided the group name is not currently being used for another autonomous group (i.e. there cannot exist two "spencers-adhoc-group.end" groups within range of each other simultaneously).\
\
Note that the fully-qualified name of the ad-hoc group ends in ".end" which is akin to saying that it has no parent (similar to the root of any "DNS tree"). Discovery of these groups can be done in the same way as normal if the group has child-groups. HOWEVER, it is important to note that the root suffix is NOT handled the same way as traditional DNS. In this system, the root-suffix does not refer to a particular DNS group or server, it simply indicates that there is nothing more to it. Thus, a DNS search for "spencers-adhoc-group.end" will never return a best-fit match for a name such as "ccrg.soe.ucsc.edu.end".}